Section 4     NUTRITION FOR HEALTHY BONES

                             by Andrea Lemieux, RNCP

        Read about Andrea Lemieux on our Meet the Team page;
                http://www.Life-Choices.com/team.html

----------

Healthy bones depend on homeostasis, or balanced body
chemistry. Both men and women suffer bone loss as they
age, and bone loss often occurs long before menopause or
any decrease in estrogen levels. Although hormones affect
bone health, we need to look at them as part of the total
picture. When the body is in balance, then our pH
(acid/alkaline measure) is correct, mineral levels are
balanced, our endocrine glands secrete the right amount
of hormones, and we produce the enzymes we need to
support the digestive process. In short, every aspect of
our internal chemistry functions in harmony.

What upsets homeostasis? The chief culprit is the consumption
of refined foods. They tend to make our blood too acidic.
When this happens, calcium is drawn from the bones in order
to bring the blood back to its slightly alkaline state.

The following should be limited or avoided as they all rob
the bones of calcium and upset body chemistry:

. Carbonated beverages are high in phosphorus, which
    disrupts the calcium/phosphorus balance. Soft drinks
    are among the worst foods imaginable for someone
    trying to prevent osteoporosis.
. Red meat because it is also high in phosphorus.
. Processed meat and cheese and baked goods are high
   in phosphorus additives.
. Excess dairy products disrupt the balance of magnesium
   and calcium.
. Refined sugar, refined flour, processed food and junk food.
. Caffeine (tea, coffee, chocolate, soft drinks) stimulates a
   release of calcium from the bones.
. Alcohol suppresses bone growth and is harmful to the
    ovaries and liver.
. Excess salt.
. Excess saturated fat (animal fat) and trans fats, found in
    margarine and processed vegetable oils.
. Tobacco. Smoking decreases natural estrogen levels,
    acidifies the blood and prevents vitamin D activation,
    which robs the bones of minerals.

Getting enough calcium in your diet is important for bone
health, but just as essential is the total composition of your
diet. Bones need magnesium, boron, copper, zinc, vitamins
A, C, D, K, the B-complex, plus essential fatty acids...just
to mention a few!! Therefore, you want to consume a nutrient-
dense diet that includes moderate amounts of animal protein,
plenty of fresh fruits and vegetables, whole grains, legumes,
nuts and seeds. Also drink at least 8 cups of pure water daily,
bones are made up of 25% water! Avoid tap water as excess
fluoride has been linked to hip fractures.

The following calcium-rich foods also contain other valuable
vitamins and minerals, and most contain necessary fiber as well:

. Sea vegetables are nature's highest source of easily absorbed
    calcium; ounce for ounce, they contain almost 10 times as
    much calcium as milk.
. Green leafy vegetables, especially kale, parsley, collards,
    dandelion leaves, and broccoli.
. Sardines and Salmon with bones (buy water-packed canned fish).
. Blackstrap molasses (unsulphured).
. Low-fat dairy products if tolerated.
. Legumes: chickpeas, lentils, beans - black, pinto, white,
    kidney, etc.
. Fresh, raw almonds, brazil nuts, and hazelnuts.
. Fresh, raw sesame seeds and sunflower seeds.
. Dried fruit (unsulphured).
. Grains: quinoa, amaranth.

Exercise is indispensable for bone health. Adding more
calcium to the diet won't necessarily result in more calcium
being deposited into the bones; a demand by the bones for
more calcium must be created through regular weight-bearing
exercise. Exercises such as walking, aerobics, and weight
lifting can not only significantly slow down the loss of bone,
but also add bone density, even in menopause. Duration of
exercise is more important than intensity, and it must be
done consistently. Outdoor exercise will add sunlight and
thus aid the body's vitamin D production, and so improve
calcium utilization. Be careful not to exercise to exhaustion;
over-exercising can cause distress which can lead to bone loss.

Calcium and magnesium supplementation has been found to
be valuable in the treatment and prevention of osteoporosis.
If you choose to take supplements, it is best to take one that
has half as much magnesium as calcium, plus vitamin D3. The
most bioavailable forms of calcium are citrate or hydroxyapatite,
even for people with deficient stomach acid, which is required
for calcium to be absorbed. The amount you take depends on
your individual situation: age, diet, level of activity, etc. Vitamin
C is also helpful because it helps create the collagenous fibers
to which the calcium of the bone is attached.


