Section 5                      
MISO SOUP

                           by Andrea Lemieux, RNCP


      Read about Andrea Lemieux on our Meet the Team page;
              http://www.Life-Choices.com/team.html


----------

This Miso Soup is made with the calcium-rich sea vegetable,
Wakame. Because of its light taste, wakame is a good choice
for new-comers. Besides calcium, wakame is high in iron and
B vitamins. It also contains many trace minerals and vitamins
A and C.

Serves 4 - 6
6 cups water or homemade, salt-free vegetable broth
2 oz. dried wakame
1-2 teaspoons extra-virgin olive oil
1 large onion, chopped
2 carrots, thinly sliced
2 stalks celery, sliced
1 teaspoon vegetable broth powder
1/2 teaspoon Celtic sea salt (gray salt)
4 tablespoons Hatcho miso (dark, soy miso)
Garnish: thinly sliced green onions

. Soak wakame in water to cover for 3 minutes, remove
    from water and carefully cut firm midriff section from the
    delicate green leaf. The midriff can be reserved for soup
    stock. Slice leaf into small pieces.
. Saute onion, carrots and celery in olive oil. When onion is
    translucent, add the water, wakame, vegetable broth powder
    and salt. Bring to a gentle boil, reduce heat, cover and simmer
    25 - 30 minutes.
. Remove the soup from heat, take 1 cup of broth from the soup,
    and stir miso into it. When miso has dissolved, mix it with the rest
    of the soup. Cover and allow to sit (away from heat) for 5 - 10
    minutes and serve garnished with green onions. Do not cook the
    miso; this destroys valuable enzymes.

Leftover soup can be reheated slightly, but never let it boil.

